<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Longer Warranties 
</P>
<P>
The House adopted, 239 to 180, an amendment toughening warranties on the 
catalytic converters and electronic control units needed to meet tailpipe 
emission standards set by the new clean air legislation (above). Auto makers 
would have to provide eight-year, 80,000-mile protection on the equipment, 
compared to the five years and 50,000 miles required by current law. 
</P>
<P>
Sponsor Gerry Sikorski (D-Minn.) said: "It is not every day in this chamber you 
get to vote for small business and environmental groups and consumers." 
</P>
<P>
Opponent Michael G. Oxley (R-Ohio) said: "The National Federation of 
Independent Business (and) the U.S. Chamber of Commerce both are on record as 
opposed to this amendment." 
</P>
<P>
A yes vote was to require longer warranties on devices to curb auto pollution. 
</P>
