<DATE>
<P>
June 3, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part M; Page 7; Column 5; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
760 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMN RIGHT; 
</P>
<P>
A PLO TRICK SHORES UP SHAMIR'S WEB; 
</P>
<P>
WE COULD BE ENSNARED BY MAKING HIS ENEMIES OUR ENEMIES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK J. BUCHANAN, Patrick J. Buchanan writes a syndicated column in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Were it not for alert Israeli forces, we would likely have seen, live on CNN, 
slaughtered sunbathers, women and children, being carried off the beaches of 
Tel Aviv as Israeli troops fought it out with suicide squads. 
</P>
<P>
Five speedboats, carrying 16 guerrillas armed with rockets and machine guns, 
were reportedly dropped off a Libyan "mother ship," 120 miles at sea. The 
guerrillas were picked up on radar 20 miles off the coast, and intercepted. 
Four were killed, 12 captured. The Palestine Liberation Front, a small, radical 
faction of the Palestine Liberation Organization, claimed responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
But, at whom was this attack aimed, besides Jews? 
</P>
<P>
One target, surely, was Yasser Arafat. Should he denounce it, only days after 
Israel brutally crushed a resurgent intifada, Arafat would appear both an 
appeaser and a weak leader unable to control his own PLO. Should he remain 
silent, the suggestion is that he approves; if he approves, Washington stops 
doing business with him. Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens was quick to 
exploit Arafat's vulnerability: "An event like this comes along . . . and 
proves something that we have been claiming all along . . . . The United States 
is holding talks with the PLO based on the assumption that the PLO has stopped 
engaging in terror." 
</P>
<P>
A second target was the moderate Arabs. A massacre would have brought Israeli 
retaliation (it still might), raising war fever, rallying Arab support for 
hawks like Iraq's Saddam Hussein, drowning out and isolating men like Egypt's 
President Hosni Mubarak. 
</P>
<P>
A third target was the peace party in Israel. Had a massacre occurred, it would 
have reduced to silence those Israeli voices who urge negotiation. 
</P>
<P>
Who benefits? First, extreme elements of the PLO who despise Arafat for dealing 
with the Americans, and want to cut his U.S. connection before it produces a 
Palestinian state on the West Bank that recognizes Israel and puts an end to 
their dream of liquidating "the Zionist entity." 
</P>
<P>
Among other beneficiaries is Yitzhak Shamir, whose party seized upon it as 
proof that its hard line against self-determination for the Palestinian people 
is the only position consistent with the safety of the Israeli people. Who can 
argue with him now? 
</P>
<P>
The answer is: We can and we must, if we do not wish to be led down a road at 
the end of which lies a Middle East war that would be a disaster for U.S. 
interests in the Arab world. 
</P>
<P>
For Shamir, the attack, like the latest Jerusalem bombing, is a godsend, making 
ancient history of his crackdown that left a dozen Palestinians dead and 900 
wounded. But the Palestinian question must not be put on a back burner. If it 
is, sooner or later, the burner will explode. 
</P>
<P>
Peace between Israel and the Arab states can never come until the core quarrel 
is addressed, a quarrel that former Foreign Minister Abba Eban describes thus: 
"Our land is a land of two histories, two tongues, two faiths, two national 
dreams, two identities. Duality is written so sharply into the very texture of 
the land that any unitary solution subjecting one nationalism to domination by 
the other is bound to be explosive and morally fragile . . . sovereignty and 
territory must be shared by two groups, not monopolized by one." 
</P>
<P>
What Eban is saying, what retired Israeli officers are saying, what a million 
Israelis have voted for, is "land for peace," a homeland on the West Bank and 
Gaza for Palestinians, in return for guarantees that land not be used as a base 
camp to attack Israel. 
</P>
<P>
Utopian? Perhaps. But repression of the Palestinians, brought to the Arab world 
on weekly television, is a formula for endless hatred. There is no guarantee 
that a Palestinian homeland will bring permanent peace; but, if there is no 
homeland, permanent war is guaranteed. 
</P>
<P>
Yitzhak Shamir, Eban writes, is a "sincere territorialist." He "opposed the 
Egyptian-Israeli treaty, the withdrawal from Lebanon, the Hussein-Peres 
agreement for a Jordanian-Palestinian solution, former U.S. Secretary of State 
George Shultz's friendly peace plan and even the renunciation of the 
inconsequential hotel on Egyptian soil in Taba." I.e., his interests are not 
our interests. 
</P>
<P>
After Suez in 1956, Great Britain extricated itself from the Middle East; but, 
after the '67 war, the United States decided to grab the tar baby. What vital 
interest of ours was at risk, in this terrible quarrel, is yet difficult to 
see. But, even if we have commitments we cannot walk away from, we must not 
give Yitzhak Shamir a blank check, to make his enemies our enemies. For they 
are legion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
