<HEADLINE>
<P>
UPDATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Daniel Cerone 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Temptations, fresh off an appearance on the season finale of "Murphy 
Brown," will hook up with CBS once again when they perform a revamped version 
of their classic Motown hit "Get Ready," to be used in the network's new fall 
promotional campaign. The tune will be featured in TV and radio spots beginning 
this summer. 
</P>
<P>
Joanna Kerns has been cast as a housewife who is emotionally and sexually 
abused by her psychiatrist in the ABC movie "Nowhere Safe." The film is a 
fictional account based on real-life facts extracted from a number of 
litigations that have taken place across the country. 
</P>
<P>
Production has begun in Los Angeles on the six-hour NBC miniseries "Jackie 
Collins' Lucky," starring Nicollette Sheridan and Vince Irizarry in a story of 
passion, power and greed. The miniseries is scheduled to be telecast in October 
as part of NBC's strategy for counter-programming this year's baseball playoffs 
on CBS. Anne-Marie Johnson, Michael Nader, Mary Frann, Stephanie Beacham, Leann 
Hunley and Eric Braeden also star. 
</P>
<P>
"The Arsenio Hall Show," trying to stay on the cutting edge, recently began 
broadcasting in Dolby Surround sound stereo -- a high-tech sound processing 
system that splits signals into four channels to create a concert-like 
ambience. "Television viewers whose homes are equipped with Surround sound 
receivers will feel as if they are part of the audience," producer Marla Kell 
Brown said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
