<HEADLINE>
<P>
MIXED MEDIA; 
</P>
<P>
** "TEX-MEX" PRODUCED/DIRECTED BY JEREMY MARRE SHANACHIE VIDEO ($19.95): ITEMS 
IN THIS SURVEY OF POP-RELATED VIDEOS, BOOKS AND LASER DISCS ARE RATED ON A 
SCALE OF ONE STAR (POOR) TO FIVE (A CLASSIC). 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON SNOWDEN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is part of "Beats of the Heart," English filmmaker Jeremy Marre's 14-part 
series that was filmed about 10 years ago and promises far more than it 
delivers. 
</P>
<P>
The documentary aims for a street-level perspective on border culture and music 
but suffers from an intrusive, banal narration. Visually, "Tex-Mex" amounts to 
little more than voyeuristic sketches that jump from subject to subject so 
arbitrarily that the handful of insightful segments seem to have slipped in by 
accident. The biggest beef: constant declarations that the music reflects 
social concerns and issues, but no translations of the lyrics for 
non-Spanish-speaking viewers. DON SNOWDEN 
</P>
</TEXT>
