<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: MAKE-BELIEVE BALLROOMS BY PETER J. SMITH (ATLANTIC MONTHLY 
PRESS: $9.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Re-warmed brat pack Angst. Ennui, drugs and alienation abound in yet another 
chronicle of life among the well-to-do but loveless kids of the Eastern 
Seaboard. 
</P>
<P>
Peter Smith's pedestrian novel takes the form of an internal monologue -- a 
polluted stream of consciousness that is too derivative to be interesting, but 
not quite terrible enough to be funny. The scene in which the narrator shaves 
his younger sister's head and his older brother's crotch may cause readers to 
wonder why a reviewer for the Chicago Tribune described Smith as a "younger, 
hipper Robert Benchley" -- and why as classy a publisher as Atlantic Monthly 
bothered with this shopworn trash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
