<HEADLINE>
<P>
MARINERS DISCOVER KNACK FOR FINDING YOUNG TALENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JIM COUR, ASSOCIATED PRESS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SEATTLE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Seattle Mariners have the two youngest players in the major leagues, and 
they're not both named Ken Griffey Jr. -- although it sometimes seems like it. 
</P>
<P>
The other 20-year-old Mariner is pitcher Brent Knackert, more or less stolen 
from the Chicago White Sox via the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
Griffey, American League Player of the Month for April, is slightly younger. 
He'll be 21 on Nov. 21, Knackert on Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
"It's still sinking in," Knackert said. "I've pitched to great players like 
Dave Winfield and Don Mattingly." 
</P>
<P>
The Mariners claimed Knackert on waivers April 5 from the Mets, who selected 
him off the White Sox roster in the Major League Rule V draft on Dec. 4. 
</P>
<P>
Since Knackert was on the White Sox Triple A roster when the Mets drafted him, 
major league rules say he must spend the season with the big-league Mariners or 
be offered back to the White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
"The White Sox didn't think anybody would take a 20-year-old kid because they 
would have to keep him in the major leagues," he said. "They wanted to teach me 
a lesson. They were shocked when they lost me. They admitted it was a stupid 
thing not to protect me after my third year." 
</P>
<P>
Especially with the kid-happy Mariners out there. The White Sox played right 
into the Mariners' hands. 
</P>
<P>
"We think Brent has a great future," Mariner General Manager Woody Woodward 
said. "It was our decision to stick with the youngster. 
</P>
<P>
"We feel certain if we offer Brent back to the White Sox, they will take him." 
</P>
<P>
Knackert was a second-round pick of the White Sox in 1987. He spent his third 
pro season with Class A Sarasota last season. 
</P>
<P>
This season, Knackert (1-0) has pitched 18 innings over 12 games and has a 3.50 
earned-run average. 
</P>
<P>
"If I only pitch 20 innings this year, it's a great experience," Knackert said. 
"I'll take this any day. I'll stay here. It's very exciting." 
</P>
<P>
Knackert's victory came in relief against California on May 3 in the Kingdome. 
That was special for him because he was born in Los Angeles and still lives in 
Huntington Beach. 
</P>
<P>
He's watching and learning while Griffey dazzles fans, opponents and teammates 
with his spectacular offense and defense. 
</P>
<P>
"He's just amazing," Knackert said. "He's a natural. It's unbelievable the 
pitches he hits. It's incredible the plays he makes. I've never seen anything 
like it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA060390-0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 228432 </DOCID>
